{"author":{"id":"50b81f7c3ab5b12c5944bd91ccafe5a65b25c709e17c4be6a6614d1147f08712"},"ops":[{"type":1,"timestamp":1604557351,"nonce":"spZHMEA4y7WZyR1CLfXtc0mhd2c=","metadata":{"github-id":"MDU6SXNzdWU3MzY2NDk3MDY=","github-url":"https://github.com/galaxyproject/tools-iuc/issues/3281","origin":"github"},"title":"Pear wrapper enhancement suggestion.","message":"Hi IUC team,\nPEAR has been the main tool I use for merging the paired-end reads for the metagenomic study since 3 years ago. I have a private Galaxy instance to handle the paired-end dataset. One of the features I have added to the existing pear wrapper is after line 49 by redirect the pear console output to a variable as the following:\nline 49  $nbase\nline 50   \u003e $logout\n\nthen I will capture the console output to a file and output to the galaxy history by appending the following code block after line 131\n\n        \u003cdata name=\"logout\" format=\"txt\" label=\"${tool.name} on ${on_string}.log\"\u003e\n          \u003cactions\u003e\n            \u003cconditional name=\"library.type\"\u003e\n              \u003cwhen value=\"paired\"\u003e\n                \u003cfilter\u003elibrary[\"type\"] == \"paired\"\u003c/filter\u003e\n              \u003c/when\u003e\n              \u003cwhen value=\"paired_collection\"\u003e\n                \u003cfilter\u003elibrary[\"type\"] == \"paired_collection\"\u003c/filter\u003e\n              \u003c/when\u003e\n            \u003c/conditional\u003e\n          \u003c/actions\u003e\n        \u003c/data\u003e\nsee here https://github.com/galaxyproject/tools-iuc/blob/57493fdc88e6128bed127993464f2a6480e2774d/tools/pear/pear.xml#L131\n\nso I can use the merged paired-end statistic from the galaxy history. The PEAR console output looks like the following\n\n|  _ \\| ____|  / \\  |  _ \\\n| |_) |  _|   / _ \\ | |_) |\n|  __/| |___ / ___ \\|  _ \u003c\n|_|   |_____/_/   \\_\\_| \\_\\\n\nPEAR v0.9.10 [May 30, 2016]\n\nCitation - PEAR: a fast and accurate Illumina Paired-End reAd mergeR\nZhang et al (2014) Bioinformatics 30(5): 614-620 | doi:10.1093/bioinformatics/btt593\n\nForward reads file.................: /mnt/galaxy/files/012/dataset_12624.dat\nReverse reads file.................: /mnt/galaxy/files/012/dataset_12625.dat\nPHRED..............................: 33\nUsing empirical frequencies........: NO\nStatistical method.................: OES\nMaximum assembly length............: 999999\nMinimum assembly length............: 50\np-value............................: 0.010000\nQuality score threshold (trimming).: 0\nMinimum read size after trimming...: 1\nMaximal ratio of uncalled bases....: 1.000000\nMinimum overlap....................: 10\nScoring method.....................: Scaled score\nThreads............................: 2\n\nAllocating memory..................: 200,000,000 bytes\nAssemblying reads: 0%\nAssemblying reads: 100%\n\n**Assembled reads ...................: 7,528 / 7,553 (99.669%)**\nDiscarded reads ...................: 0 / 7,553 (0.000%)\nNot assembled reads ...............: 25 / 7,553 (0.331%)\nAssembled reads file...............: pear.assembled.fastq\nDiscarded reads file...............: pear.discarded.fastq\nUnassembled forward reads file.....: pear.unassembled.forward.fastq\nUnassembled reverse reads file.....: pear.unassembled.reverse.fastq\n\n\nIt will be great if the feature can be made available .\n\nMany thanks,\nMike","files":null}]}